</node>
<node id="Randomized Study">
  <data key="d0">Randomized Study</data>
  <data key="d1">event</data>
  <data key="d2">A randomized clinical study evaluating the feasibility and safety of Impella LP2.5 compared to IABP in patients with cardiogenic shock caused by acute myocardial infarction.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ca971059e15553c9f065f9d48ca96130</data>
  <data key="d4">mineru_seyfarth2008.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836746</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Hemodynamic Support">
  <data key="d0">Hemodynamic Support</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The assistance of cardiac function to maintain adequate blood circulation, provided by mechanical devices.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ca971059e15553c9f065f9d48ca96130</data>
  <data key="d4">mineru_seyfarth2008.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836746</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Hemolysis">
  <data key="d0">Hemolysis</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A condition of red blood cell destruction, observed as a transitory increase in Impella patients.&lt;SEP&gt;A secondary end point evaluated in the study.&lt;SEP&gt;Hemolysis, assessed by measurements of free hemoglobin, was significantly higher in Impella patients during the first 24 hours.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ca971059e15553c9f065f9d48ca96130&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7d070016888b87e5d8407655292c6a98&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-40ef920a3d882cbe9feb69d377f883e2</data>
  <data key="d4">mineru_seyfarth2008.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836746</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
