  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Propionic Acidemia">
  <data key="d0">Propionic Acidemia</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Propionic Acidemia (PA) is a severe metabolic disorder characterized by multiorgan pathology, including renal disease, and carries a marked risk for complications like chronic kidney disease.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-94e6c2d3a322064c0bedf6b639e576b4</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836884</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Chronic Kidney Disease">
  <data key="d0">Chronic Kidney Disease</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) is categorized into stages (G2-G4), with its prevalence assessed differently by creatinine and cystatin C eGFR equations.&lt;SEP&gt;Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) is narrowly defined as a glomerular filtration rate &lt;60 mL/min/1.73 m2, and is an under-recognized complication in Propionic Acidemia, especially in adults.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-94e6c2d3a322064c0bedf6b639e576b4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b85f53c31ce42d37f83b5008e14bf203</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836884</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Estimated Glomerular Filtration Rate">
  <data key="d0">Estimated Glomerular Filtration Rate</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Estimated Glomerular Filtration Rate (eGFR) is a measure of renal function that shows an age-dependent decline in PA patients, with standard equations showing poor predictive performance.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-94e6c2d3a322064c0bedf6b639e576b4</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836884</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Creatinine eGFR">
  <data key="d0">Creatinine eGFR</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A method for estimating glomerular filtration rate using serum creatinine, which yields higher estimates in PA patients compared to cystatin C eGFR.&lt;SEP&gt;Estimated glomerular filtration rate calculated using creatinine-based equations, which classified fewer patients as having CKD compared to cystatin C.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b85f53c31ce42d37f83b5008e14bf203</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Cystatin C eGFR">
  <data key="d0">Cystatin C eGFR</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A method for estimating glomerular filtration rate using cystatin C, which provides lower GFR estimates in PA patients compared to creatinine-based equations.&lt;SEP&gt;Estimated glomerular filtration rate calculated using cystatin C-based equations, which classified a significantly higher percentage of patients with reduced eGFR.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b85f53c31ce42d37f83b5008e14bf203</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="PA">
  <data key="d0">PA</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">PA is a medical condition where patients have minimal hepatic capacity to metabolize propionic acid, requiring renal excretion to clear toxic metabolites, and is associated with renal insufficiency and CKD.&lt;SEP&gt;Propionic acidemia, a metabolic condition associated with a high prevalence of chronic kidney disease and reduced whole-body creatine synthesis.&lt;SEP&gt;PA (Propionic Acidemia) is the condition affecting the subjects in the study, characterized by biallelic pathogenic variants in PCCA or PCCB.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b85f53c31ce42d37f83b5008e14bf203</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="CKD">
  <data key="d0">CKD</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">CKD (Chronic Kidney Disease) is a renal condition that can progress in PA patients, requiring surveillance and renal protective therapies to delay its onset or progression.&lt;SEP&gt;Chronic kidney disease, defined by an eGFR of less than 60 mL/min/1.73 m2, showing an unexpectedly high prevalence of 50% in adult PA patients.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Serum Creatinine">
  <data key="d0">Serum Creatinine</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">A biomarker for kidney function found to have lower-than-average concentrations in PA patients, potentially due to impaired growth, sarcopenia, or diet.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Cystatin C">
  <data key="d0">Cystatin C</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Cystatin C is a laboratory measurement suggested to be useful as part of CKD surveillance in PA subjects.&lt;SEP&gt;A biomarker for kidney function that is associated with parameters of renal dysfunction like plasma lipocalin-2 and shows different estimation trends than creatinine in PA.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Creatinine Excretion">
  <data key="d0">Creatinine Excretion</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">The amount of creatinine excreted in urine, found to be below average in PA patients, suggesting reduced whole-body creatine synthesis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Whole-Body Creatine Synthesis">
  <data key="d0">Whole-Body Creatine Synthesis</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A biological process likely reduced in PA patients due to a combination of dietary and metabolic influences, leading to lower plasma creatinine.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Bedside Schwartz Creatinine-Based Equation">
  <data key="d0">Bedside Schwartz Creatinine-Based Equation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A 2009 equation used to estimate GFR from creatinine, resulting in significantly higher GFR estimates in younger PA patients compared to cystatin C-based equations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Plasma Lipocalin-2">
  <data key="d0">Plasma Lipocalin-2</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">A laboratory parameter associated with serum creatinine and cystatin C, suggesting a role in ongoing tubular injury in the etiology of CKD in PA.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="E-IMD Registry">
  <data key="d0">E-IMD Registry</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">A registry that reported a lower prevalence of CKD (approximately 15%) in adult PA patients compared to the current study.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="MMA">
  <data key="d0">MMA</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Methylmalonic acidemia, another organic acidemia associated with nearly universal prevalence of CKD and similar associations with plasma lipocalin-2.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-98cbd727a53cb48f6ceb663b70bfe869</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Plasma Uric Acid">
  <data key="d0">Plasma Uric Acid</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Plasma uric acid is a laboratory measurement suggested to be useful as part of CKD surveillance in PA subjects.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="25-OH-Vitamin D">
  <data key="d0">25-OH-Vitamin D</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">25-OH-vitamin D is a laboratory measurement suggested to be useful as part of CKD surveillance in PA subjects.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="1,25-OH-Vitamin D">
  <data key="d0">1,25-OH-Vitamin D</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">1,25-OH-vitamin D is a laboratory measurement suggested to be useful as part of CKD surveillance in PA subjects.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="PTH">
  <data key="d0">PTH</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">PTH is a laboratory measurement suggested to be useful as part of CKD surveillance in PA subjects.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Plasma Osmolality">
  <data key="d0">Plasma Osmolality</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Plasma osmolality is a laboratory measurement suggested to be useful as part of CKD surveillance in PA subjects.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="24-Hour Protein Excretion">
  <data key="d0">24-Hour Protein Excretion</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">24-hour protein excretion is a laboratory measurement suggested to be useful as part of CKD surveillance in PA subjects.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Renal Protective Therapies">
  <data key="d0">Renal Protective Therapies</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Renal protective therapies are treatments aimed at delaying the onset or slowing the progression of CKD, including aggressive control of acid/base status, blood pressure control, and urate-lowering therapy.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Renin–Angiotensin System Inhibition">
  <data key="d0">Renin–Angiotensin System Inhibition</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Inhibition of the renin–angiotensin system is a method used to control blood pressure as part of renal protective therapies.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Urate-Lowering Therapy">
  <data key="d0">Urate-Lowering Therapy</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Urate-lowering therapy is a treatment used to delay the onset or progression of CKD.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ecea5c0d8fe77f18274ef9e323deab43</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1779836885</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
